In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims August 26, 2011, as Women's Equality Day in the United States. He acknowledges the significance of the 19th Amendment to the Constitution, which granted women the right to vote and paved the way for their participation in the political process. The President recognizes the efforts of trailblazing women who fought for gender equality and emphasizes the need to continue working towards equal rights for all. He highlights his administration's commitment to advancing equality, including addressing issues women face in employment, healthcare, and sexual assault. The President calls upon the American people to celebrate the achievements of women and strive for gender equality.